column1: # text_orig = Dat Röberpack hett hier Anno Söss to gottlos hus't, wat ik as Jung betügen kann, denn mi hett dunmals en Schafför en Ohrfieg staken, as se mi min Lewdag nich wedder an den Kopp flagen is.
# remark = "to gottlos" is likely a structural borrowing from Standard German ("zu gottlos"). This is characteristic for 19th c. written Low German.
# variety = East Low German, North Markian (Nordmärkisch)
# text_orig = Fritz un Gottfried weern twungen, still to hollen un müßten Tokiker sin von de Ding', de da vör sik gahn sullen.
# remark = Influenced by Fritz Reuter, Hill writes /a/ instead of conventional å (oa)
# variety = East Low German, Central Pomeranian (Mittelpommersch)

# text_orig = Dag's un nachts was se immer prat, ehr Schützling', so as de Kluck ehr Küken, vör Undœg' to bewohren, un dat müsst ehr de Neid laten, dat se met ehr Husmiddel gegen Kinnerkrankheiten al anner Frugens in'n Urt den Dum upt Og' drücken ded'.
# remark = “dag’s un nachts” could be influenced by standard German, a modern equivalent would be “Dach un Nacht” (no case)
# variety = East Low German, North Markian (Nordmärkisch)
# text_orig = He was as 'n armen Jungen nah Berlin kamen und hadd sich dörch Singen in 'd Domchor un nohstens an de Oper verdeenen müßt, um so väl to hebben, dat he stodeeren lehren künn.
# remark = “um” is possibly a typo for Low German üm, “und” is certainly one for “un”
# variety = East Low German, Central Pomeranian (Mittelpommersch)
